@@eThe Roc Road -- As Kowloon Sees It@@N

@@eCourier Lantern Office, Western Intelligence Summary@@N

The Roc Road connects @@yMidgaard@@N to @@yKiess@@N. It does not connect
to Kowloon. This defines our entire relationship with the corridor:
we watch it, we price its disruptions, and we do not depend on it.

The Road is a @@ynegotiated artery@@N between two civilizations we trade
with but do not belong to. Midgaard governs by stone law. Kiess
governs by adaptive commerce. The Harbor Syndics note with detachment:
@@ywe survive because we face the sea@@N, not because we built a road
to a rival.

On Midgaard's half, stone paving, patrol relays, and the @@WThree
Civic Oaths@@N recited at every shift change. The Wardens of Iron
note: @@dpainted boundary sigils do not stop ash, flood, or famine@@N.
On Kiess's half, convoy marshals manage flow through shared liability
pools. The Harbor Syndics recognize @@ythis@@N -- risk distribution is
harbor doctrine by another name.

The central @@rCrossroads@@N is the corridor's political heart. The
Jade Magistracy tracks its instability because @@rCrossroads disruption
affects goods prices continent-wide@@N. When Midgaard and Kiess fight
over the center, luxury goods arrive through our @@lTide Gate@@N by sea
instead. We do not wish for war on the Roc Road, but we price its
interruptions carefully.

The @@dViolet Eclipse Cathedral@@N along the route troubles the Temple
Circle. Procurement ledgers and binding archives suggest souls treated
as @@radministrative material@@N. The Temple Circle's doctrine: the dead
are named, honored, released -- not @@dbound into archives@@N.

Kiess was @@ybuilt on Evermeet's ruins@@N, with a founding clause that
no sealed warrant from a predecessor binds a Kiess citizen. Kowloon's
@@yNeon Covenant@@N carries a similar refusal -- but where Kiess
repudiates sealed warrants with rhetoric, we repudiate them with
@@ephosphorescent ink@@N: material guarantee against forgery in darkness.

The Road asks: @@W"Who has lawful right to command?"@@N versus @@y"What
keeps people alive?"@@N Kowloon's answer is neither. We ask: @@e"Who
keeps the lanterns lit?"@@N Authority that does not maintain
infrastructure is performance. The Roc Road performs. We work.

The Courier Lantern Office files it under @@yexternal disruption
risk@@N: relevant to pricing, irrelevant to survival. The Roc Road is
someone else's argument. We watch it the way a harbor watches a
distant storm -- @@ynoting direction, calculating arrival, checking
our own moorings@@N.
